# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-g-barr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-g-barr/3i-infrastructure] The company was launched by way of an initial public offering in 2007.
[src:a-g-barr/3i-infrastructure] Its early investments included Anglian Water Group and Oiltanking GmbH's terminal facilities in the Netherlands, Malta, and Singapore.
[src:a-g-barr/3i-infrastructure] Between 2010 and 2020, 3i Infrastructure invested in businesses such as Esvagt, Infinis and Wireless Infrastructure Group, a UK mobile infrastructure provider.
[src:a-g-barr/3i-infrastructure] Since 2021, the company’s new investments have included SRL Traffic Systems, a UK manufacturer and supplier of temporary traffic equipment, and Global Cloud Xchange.
[src:a-g-barr/3i-infrastructure] About 29.2% of the company is owned by 3i Group plc.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] The company was founded by Dick Nelson as Nelson Marketing in Logansport, Indiana in 1985.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] It was acquired by Bemrose Corporation in 1996.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] In 2000, Bemrose Corporation exited the paper products business and changed its name to 4imprint Group plc.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] Its North America division was renamed 4imprint Inc.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] In 2003, Hanover Investors, a private equity firm, purchased over 25% of 4imprint over the course of a month.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] They led a shareholder rebellion, and shareholders called for the removal of all non-executive directors after talks between 4imprint and Hanover Investors broke down.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] 4imprint established a distribution center in Oshkosh, Wisconsin in 2009.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] In 2012, it sold Kreyer Promotion Service GmbH and Brand Addition Limited to European affiliate companies of H.I.G.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] In November 2024, the company was identified as one of the best performing shares on the London Stock Exchange over the last decade having achieved a 16% increase in share price since 2023, a 111% increase in share price since 2022, and a 2,342% increase in share price since 2011.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] However, the company expressed some caution about sales growth and said it would be slower in 2024 than in the previous year.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] In October 2024, the company completed the expansion of its Oshkosh operations.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] The 170,000 expansion brought the total size of the facility to 475,000-square-foot.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] The development involved 1,488 new solar panels and brought the total on the building to some 4,000 panels.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] This was part of a programme to expand its North American headquarters in Oshkosh announced in 2015.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] The State of Wisconsin, through its Wisconsin Economic Development Corporation, may have supported the company with state tax credits, dependent upon the number of jobs that were actually created through the expansion.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] This large facility is home to some 50% of the total workforce.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] Although headquartered in London, 97% of 4imprint's business is in the United States and Canada.
[src:a-g-barr/4imprint] In both 2023 and 2024, it was ranked the largest distributor by revenue in promotional products industry in North America.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The company was founded in 1875 by Robert Barr in Falkirk.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In 1887, his son, Robert Fulton Barr, set up a division of the original company in Glasgow, which had a much larger population.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In 1892 the Glasgow branch passed to Andrew Greig Barr (where the name A.G.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr comes from), a brother of the branch's founder.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In 1899, they soft launched Irn-Bru, eventually launching it in 1901.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The Falkirk and Glasgow divisions merged in 1959, and the company was listed on the London Stock Exchange in 1965.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In 2001 the company acquired Findlays Mineral Water which is sourced in the Lammermuir Hills.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr as managing director, and in 2004 became the first chief executive from outside the Barr family.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The company acquired Forfar-based Strathmore Mineral Water in May 2006.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The Irn-Bru 32 energy drink variant was launched in 2006.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In 2008, the company purchased the Taut sports drink range, and exotic fruit drink company Rubicon.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr began production and distribution of Rockstar Energy for the United Kingdom and Republic of Ireland.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] This contract was terminated in 2020, following the acquisition by PepsiCo.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In November 2012, the company agreed to merge with Britvic, which produces drinks like J2O, Tango and Robinsons, as well as holding the authority to produce Pepsi for the UK market, to create one of Europe's largest soft drinks companies.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr signed a 10-year deal with Dr Pepper Snapple Group to sell, market and distribute the Snapple brand in the UK and some of Europe.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The company acquired a cocktail mixer business, Funkin, in February 2015.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In December 2022, the company acquired Boost Drinks for £20 million from founders Simon and Alison Gray.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The company also took full control of Moma Foods at that time.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr had acquired the Rio Tropical Limited soft drinks brand from the independent brewer and pub company, Hall and Woodhouse Limited, for £12.3 million.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr announced plans to discontinue Strathmore bottled water in a move that could see the closure of its Forfar factory; however, in July 2025 the brand was acquired by Tŷ Nant which safeguarded the jobs.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr acquired a majority stake in Innate-Essence Limited, parent company of The Turmeric Co.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] In February 2026, the company announced that it was to acquire Hexham-based Fentimans for £38 million and Devon-based Frobishers for £13 million.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] On 14 July 1961, the Coca-Cola Company asked Lord Walker for an interim interdict about the type of bottle used by A.G.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr's "*Kolabar*", "*Cydrap*" and "*Stilkrush*" in the Court of Session.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Coca-Cola's argument was that "real danger that the bottle used by [A.G.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr] for containing Kolabar will be mistaken by the public for [Coca-Cola].", while A.G.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr's argument was "the position of Coca-Cola in the soft drinks industry in Scotland is insignificant in comparison with that of [A.G.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Lord Walker refused the interim interdict, as a large part of their business could've been disturbed, additionally because Coca-Cola made no sales in the country at that point.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] Barr produces a variety of soft drinks from production sites at Cumbernauld, and Milton Keynes.
[src:a-g-barr/a-g-barr] The company has also previously had production sites in Atherton, Falkirk, Forfar, Mansfield, Parkhead (Glasgow), Pitcox and Tredegar.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] The company was established by a manager based in Singapore, Hugh Young, as part of a strategic push towards investments in the Asia Pacific Region in the early-1990s.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] It was launched as Abtrust Asian Smaller Companies Investment Trust in September 1995, changed its name to Aberdeen Asian Smaller Companies Investment Trust in December 1997 and then changed it again to Abrdn Asian Smaller Companies Investment Trust in November 2018.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] It adopted the name, Abrdn Asia Focus, in April 2022.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] In November 2021, the company removed the restriction, which had limited the market capitalisation of companies in which invested to US$1.5 billion.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] The change was intended to encourage investment in a broader range of companies, especially in the growing economy of China.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] Young stepped down in December 2023 and was replaced by Flavia Cheong.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] However, in May 2025, the company announced that Cheong would retire and would be replaced by Pruksa Iamthongthong in December 2025.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] It is managed by Aberdeen Group and the chair is Krishna Shanmuganathan who took over that role in 2022.
[src:a-g-barr/aberdeen-asia-focus] It changed its name again to Aberdeen Asia Focus in October 2025.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] The company was formed to consolidate a series of palm oil plantations in 1985.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] These included part of the Tasik Estate in the South Labuhanbatu Regency in North Sumatra, a province of Indonesia.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] In May 1989, Chillington Corporation took a 52.2% shareholding in the company.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] After the company's previous majority shareholder got into financial difficulties, Genton International acquired a controlling holding in the company in October 1993.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] In August 2024, the company invested in a large compressed natural gas plant at the Tasik Raja Palm Oil Mill in the South Labuhanbatu Regency.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] The company changed its name to AEP Plantations in November 2025.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] As of November 2024, the company operated 121,655 hectares (300,620 acres) of plantations in Indonesia and 65,881 hectares (162,800 acres) of plantations in Malaysia.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] As of September 2025, through Genton International, the estate of Lim Siew Kim owned about 51% of the company.
[src:a-g-barr/aep-plantations] Lim Siew Kim (died 2022) was the daughter of Lim Goh Tong (died 2007), who founded the Genting Group.
[src:a-g-barr/aj-bell] The company was formed in Manchester by Andrew (Andy) James Bell and Nicholas Littlefair in 1995.
[src:a-g-barr/aj-bell] The company was the subject of an initial public offering valuing the business at £675 million in November 2018.
[src:a-g-barr/aj-bell] The company also provides third party SIPP administration services, and owns a specialist financial publishing business in London known as AJ Bell Media.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The company was founded under the name *Appliances Online* by John Roberts in 2000.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Prior to this, during a conversation in a Bolton pub, a close friend bet Roberts £1 that he could not set up his own company and disrupt the white goods market by selling appliances online.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] As well as selling directly to consumers, the company also sold kitchen appliances on behalf of other retailers such as Next, House of Fraser and B&Q.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In 2009 the company acquired the distribution business Expert Logistics, enabling end-to-end control of their operation.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In 2013 *Appliances Online* rebranded to *AO.com*, which included a redesign of their logo to its current state.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In February 2014, the company was floated on the London Stock Exchange as AO World.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The IPO allowed the company to raise funds for European expansion.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In 2015 AO.com announced plans for their second overseas website, AO.nl In the same year, a number of AO employees completed a Germany to Bolton bike ride to raise money for a new playground.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In 2016 to support its European expansion, AO opened its 84,000-square-metre (900,000 sq ft) headquarters in Bergheim, Germany.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In 2017 the company announced it would sponsor the 11th series of ITV show, *Britain's Got Talent*.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] It also announced that it would extend its sponsorship with Lancashire County Cricket Club.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] It was also reported that company founder, Roberts, would step down as CEO, remaining on the board as founder and executive director.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The former COO, Steve Caunce, took over as CEO.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In March, the company announced that it had raised £50 million through share placing to support plans for further growth.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The retailer also announced that it was to open a recycling plant in Telford, Shropshire.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In January 2018, the retailer reported that it had opened a new office in Manchester city centre, which was to be home to the business's in-house multimedia, IT and sales teams.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In April, the business announced that it had become one of only 20 businesses in the world to have received over 100,000 Trustpilot reviews.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In July, the business launched its new brand campaign, Delivering Tomorrow.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] It was also reported that it had committed to building a second major fridge recycling facility in the south east of England.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The company also confirmed that it had completed the acquisition of the online phone retailer Mobile Phones Direct for £32.5 million, as it looked to expand its offering in the mobile phone sector.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In January 2019, it was announced that Caunce would step down as CEO and Roberts would reassume the role.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] AO's recycling plant in Telford processed its millionth fridge in July 2019.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] AO Mobile launched in August 2019, offering all UK mobile networks and all handset manufacturers.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Roberts described the launch as "a game changer for mobile phone customers".
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In August 2019, AO launched AO Finance in partnership with consumer finance provider NewDay.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] AO Finance offers a rolling credit facility that gives customers access to essential products through affordable finance.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In October 2019, AO's plastic plant was unveiled as the company announced its ambition to use its recycling capabilities to ultimately make new fridges from the recycled materials extracted from old ones.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Announcing its interim financial results in November 2019, Roberts confirmed that AO would close its operation in the Netherlands to focus on its German business.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Roberts explained that the team did not have the bandwidth to fix both markets but remained committed to future international expansion once the German model was proven.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In April 2020, AO Business continued to grow and after only six months in the housebuilders sector, secured over 12,000 building plots.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Following a strategic review in July 2022, AO exited the housebuilder market to focus on business-to-business sectors that better fitted its model.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] This includes kitchen manufacturers and retailers, such as its partnership with Homebase, which launched in January 2022.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In September 2020, AO announced that it would be the new headline sponsor of Manchester Arena.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The announcement came as operators ASM Global were submitting a planning application for phase one of its redevelopment.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In a five-year deal, the rebranded AO Arena would see live events resuming once the COVID-19-related restrictions on venues were lifted.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In October 2020, AO announced plans to open five 'stores-within-a-store' with Tesco as part of a six-month partnership trial with the supermarket.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Following the launch of its Value Creation Plan in 2020, an all employee long-term incentive that rewards exceptional value creation, AO announced a restructuring of the plan in September 2022, which saw the scheme begin funding at a share price of £1.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In June 2022, AO closed its German business, which accounted for around 10% of the group's revenue.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The following month, AO successfully completed a planned £40 million capital raise to strengthen its balance sheet and increase liquidity.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In Autumn 2022, AO appointed two new non-executive directors to its board.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Former Pets at Home chief executive, Peter Pritchard, joined in September and Pret a Manger global chief digital officer Sarah Venning joined in November 2022.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] At its half year financial results in November 2022, AO upgraded its full year profit expectations following its strategic pivot to focus on cash generation and profitability, which included reducing its cost base by £30 million.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In the same month, AO announced it was the new headline sponsor of Manchester Thunder, the current and four time Netball Super League champions.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] AO announced in October 2024 that it would acquire musicMagpie, an online retailer that buys and sells refurbished electronics, for approximately £10 million, as part of expanding the firm's consumer tech businesses.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In June 2026, AO.com exceeded one million reviews on Trustpilot with an overall average rating of 4.9 out of 5.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The company now occupies 50,000 sq ft (4,600 m2) offices and is based in Bolton.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The company launched a new advertising campaign on 3 May 2013 to mark the rebranding of the business from Appliances Online to ao.com.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The first advert follows a fictional new employee called 'Dave' and his over-enthusiastic inductor on his first day at work.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] A further advert was aired showing 'Barry Catchpole'.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] Its adverts feature a version of the Ramones song "Blitzkrieg Bop" in which the words "Hey!
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] In May 2020, AO launched a new advertising campaign with an advert showing how Britain's homes were working harder than ever whilst many people were forced to stay home due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:a-g-barr/ao-world] The advert demonstrated the hundreds of thousands of electricals AO have in stock ready for next day delivery across the UK.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] The company was established in 1889 as the Transvaal Mortgage Loan and Finance Company, led by chairman W.J.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] Thompson, and invested in what is now South Africa.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] It was renamed the British Empire Land Mortgage and Loan Company in 1906, and British Empire Securities and General Trust in 1964.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] Asset Value Investors, an employee-owned management company, was established to manage the firm, then valued at £6 million, in 1985.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] The company's goal of acquiring other companies trading below their Net Asset Value led it to attempt takeovers of other investment trusts trading at a discount.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] In 1986, the company acquired Ashdown Investment Trust for £66 million.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] In 1989, it mounted a hostile takeover bid for Schroder Global Trust: it had been building up a stake in the target company over a two-year period.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] In 1995, it acquired the Selective Assets Trust (formerly the Edinburgh Assets Trust) for £42 million.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] It simplified its name from British Empire Securities and General Trust to British Empire Trust in 2015.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] In 2016, the activist US hedge fund, Elliott Management Corporation, built up a large stake in the company.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] The investment was seen as one of Elliott's successful investment positions in the UK.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] It changed its name from British Empire Trust to AVI Global Trust in May 2019.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] Between 2019 and 2020, the company invested heavily in SoftBank Group and other Japanese stocks.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] The company's strategy has been to take advantage of Softbank's share buyback programme.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] This has supported the company's market capitalisation on the London Stock Exchange which was £751 million in July 2020.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] It has also built up a significant holding in Pershing Square Holdings, a hedge fund.
[src:a-g-barr/avi-global-trust] AVI became signatories of the Principles for Responsible Investment (PRI) in April 2021.
